File System Hierarchy 

/ (Root) : Root Location
         - Like a windows C drive this is the home location of Linux O.S

/home : guest user
        - admin user is root user

/usr : (User Program & Binaries)
        - this location of file system includes software files and libraries

/bin, /sbin : (Essential binaries)
            - Contains essential user and system administration binaries.
            - Example: ls, cp, mv, cat.

/etc :  System configuration files are stored here.
        - Example: network configs, user configs.

/tmp : - Temporary files created by applications.
       - Files may be deleted after reboot.

/dev : - Contains device files representing hardware devices.
        - Example: disks, USB devices, terminals.

/proc : Virtual filesystem that provides process and kernel information.

/sys : Contain system information

/var : - Stores variable data such as logs, mail, and spool files.
- Example: /var/log

Please find below linux file tree :

/ (Root)
├── bin        # Essential user binaries (ls, cp, mv)
├── boot       # Boot loader files and kernel
├── dev        # Device files
├── etc        # Configuration files
├── home       # User home directories
│   └── user
├── lib        # Shared libraries
├── media      # Removable media (USB, CD)
├── mnt        # Temporary mount point
├── opt        # Optional software
├── proc       # Process information (virtual filesystem)
├── root       # Root user home directory
├── run        # Runtime system information
├── sbin       # System binaries (admin commands)
├── tmp        # Temporary files
├── usr        # User programs and utilities
│   ├── bin
│   ├── lib
│   └── share
└── var        # Variable data (logs, mail)
    └── log

